<methodology slug="ai-agent-patterns">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>ai</group>
    <domain>ai-agents</domain>
    <summary>Control flow patterns for AI agents: Chain of Thought, ReAct, Plan-and-Execute, Tool Use. Pattern selection drives task success more than model size.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>agents</tag>
      <tag>patterns</tag>
      <tag>frameworks</tag>
      <tag>orchestration</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-25</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>AI Agent Patterns</title>
    <summary>Fundamental control flow patterns for AI agents. Chain of Thought (CoT) for reasoning-only tasks, ReAct (Reason + Act) for tool-dependent work, Plan-and-Execute for multi-step projects, Tool Use Pattern for framework-based agents. Framework selection (LangGraph, AutoGen, CrewAI, OpenAI Agents SDK) depends on pattern complexity.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Simple prompt to response is insufficient for complex tasks. Agents that solve interesting problems require a structured control flow that allows reasoning, tool use, and iteration. Different task types benefit from different control patterns. Choosing the right pattern based on task structure is more impactful than upgrading the underlying model. An agent with no pattern (just chaining prompts) fails more often than a well-structured agent on a smaller model.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <p>Apply this methodology the moment you start a new agent task and must decide between a single LLM call, a CoT prompt, a ReAct loop, or a Plan-and-Execute graph. Re-apply whenever an existing agent loops, hallucinates, or fails to use tools — pattern mismatch is the most common root cause.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Choosing a control flow pattern (CoT, ReAct, Plan-and-Execute) for a new agent task</item>
        <item>Explaining why a single prompt-response fails and what pattern would address the gap</item>
        <item>Selecting a framework (LangGraph, AutoGen, CrewAI, OpenAI Agents SDK) for a new agent project</item>
        <item>Debugging an agent that loops, hallucinates, or fails to use tools correctly where pattern mismatch is often the root cause</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Tasks solvable in a single LLM call where adding an agent pattern introduces latency and token overhead with no benefit</item>
        <item>Creative generation tasks where strict control flow degrades output quality</item>
        <item>When the framework dependency cost exceeds the project lifetime (e.g., a one-off script using LangGraph)</item>
        <item>Hard real-time tasks where multi-iteration loops are too slow (under 500 milliseconds SLA)</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <how-to>
      <step>1. Classify the task. Answer three questions in writing: (a) Does the task need external information not in the prompt? (b) Are there sequential subtasks with dependencies? (c) Is the answer derivable by pure reasoning over given context? Based on answers: pure reasoning → CoT; needs tools, ≤5 steps, simple → ReAct; needs tools, &gt;5 steps or branching → Plan-and-Execute.</step>
      <step>2. Pick the pattern using the decision rule in step 1. Write the chosen pattern at the top of the implementation file as a comment so reviewers see the intent.</step>
      <step>3. Pick the framework. Single agent + simple loop → raw anthropic SDK with tool_use. Stateful Plan-and-Execute or branching graphs → LangGraph. Multi-agent debate → AutoGen. Role-based crews → CrewAI. Strict OpenAI stack → OpenAI Agents SDK.</step>
      <step>4. Define tools with strict JSON schemas. Each tool: name, one-sentence description, input schema with required fields, deterministic output (JSON, not prose).</step>
      <step>5. Wire the loop with three guards: max_steps cap, loop-detection (break if last 3 (action,args) tuples are identical), and replan trigger (Plan-and-Execute only — call replan when any step status != "completed").</step>
      <step>6. Add tracing. Either LangSmith or a manual log of (step_index, thought, action, args, observation, tokens_in, tokens_out) per iteration to a JSONL file.</step>
      <step>7. Run on a 10-20 task benchmark with known answers before production. Measure success_rate, avg_steps, p95_tokens, loop_break_count.</step>
      <step>8. Ship behind a feature flag. Compare metrics against the previous pattern for at least one full daily cycle before removing the flag.</step>
    </how-to>
    <section name="Agent Design Patterns Overview">
      <p>The fundamental problem is that simple prompt to response is insufficient. Complex tasks require the model to reason about intermediate results, decide whether more information is needed, and iterate. Different agent patterns address different task requirements:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Chain of Thought (CoT) — "Let's think step by step." Output: Reasoning, Intermediate steps, Final answer. Best for pure reasoning without external tools.</item>
        <item>ReAct (Reason + Act) — Thought, Action, Observation, Repeat. Thought: What do I need? Action: search(query). Observation: search results. Best for research and investigation.</item>
        <item>Plan-and-Execute — Create plan with subtasks, Execute each subtask, Verify results, Adjust plan if needed, Synthesize final output. Best for complex projects.</item>
        <item>Tool Use Pattern — Agent decides which tool to use based on task. Tools have schemas. Best for framework-based implementations.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Pattern Details and Framework Mapping">
      <p>Chain of Thought (CoT) prompts the model to think through the problem step-by-step before answering. This works well on Claude and GPT-4 class models for reasoning tasks, but degrades on smaller models. CoT alone has no tool access and no iteration.</p>
      <p>ReAct adds tool use and observation loops. The agent reasons about what it needs, calls a tool, observes the result, and reasons again. This naturally handles tool-dependent research tasks. However, ReAct can get stuck in repetitive loops if tool results are ambiguous.</p>
      <p>Plan-and-Execute decomposes the goal upfront into subtasks with dependencies, then executes each step. This prevents the agent from getting stuck mid-task by committing to a full plan first. The tradeoff is that plans become stale if early steps produce unexpected results.</p>
      <p>Tool Use Pattern is a framework-level abstraction where the model selects from a set of available tools based on the task. This is how LangGraph, AutoGen, CrewAI, and OpenAI Agents SDK work. Tools are defined with schemas, and the framework handles tool calling, result injection, and retry logic.</p>
      <p>Frameworks map to patterns as follows: LangGraph supports state machines for Plan-and-Execute and complex ReAct. AutoGen handles multi-agent conversations. CrewAI provides role-based agent teams. OpenAI Agents SDK provides official OpenAI support with tight model coupling.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="When Pattern Fails and Limitations">
      <p>Chain of Thought (CoT) degrades on tasks requiring factual recall; the model reasons confidently to wrong conclusions. If the model has never learned the answer during training, CoT cannot recover that knowledge.</p>
      <p>ReAct (Reason + Act) loops can get stuck in circular Thought, Action, Observation cycles without progress if the tool returns ambiguous results. The agent may call the same tool twice with slightly different arguments, getting similar unhelpful results both times.</p>
      <p>Plan-and-Execute breaks when the initial plan is wrong and the replanning step is not implemented. Agents proceed to execute an invalid plan to completion instead of stopping to revise the plan.</p>
      <p>Framework abstractions (LangGraph state machines, AutoGen conversations) add debugging complexity; errors manifest several layers below the business logic.</p>
      <p>Tool Use Pattern requires precise tool descriptions; vague descriptions cause the agent to select the wrong tool or pass malformed arguments.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow and Model Selection">
      <p>Use Claude Haiku to generate initial tool definitions from an API schema (mechanical transformation). Use Claude Sonnet to review agent reasoning chains (requires logic analysis across multiple steps). Use Claude Opus only when designing multi-agent orchestration where coordination patterns are genuinely complex. For production NERO pipelines, ReAct is the default pattern; Plan-and-Execute is used when a task has more than 5 sequential steps requiring inter-step dependencies.</p>
      <p>Model selection by task: Haiku for tool definition generation from API schemas (mechanical, no reasoning). Sonnet for reviewing agent reasoning chains (requires logic analysis). Opus for designing multi-agent orchestration (complex coordination).</p>
    </section>
    <checklist>
      <check>Task classified in writing: needs-tools (yes/no), step-count (n), branching (yes/no).</check>
      <check>Pattern chosen by decision rule and recorded as a comment at the top of the agent file.</check>
      <check>Framework chosen and pinned in requirements (e.g. langgraph==0.2.x).</check>
      <check>Each tool has name, one-sentence description, JSON schema with required fields, and deterministic JSON output.</check>
      <check>max_steps guard set (default 15) and triggers a controlled error, not a silent retry.</check>
      <check>Loop-detection guard: break when the last 3 (action, args_hash) tuples are identical.</check>
      <check>Plan-and-Execute only: replan node is wired and triggered on any step status != "completed".</check>
      <check>Tracing wired (LangSmith run URL or JSONL log path) and verified to contain at least one full trace.</check>
      <check>Benchmark of 10-20 known-answer tasks executed; success_rate, avg_steps, p95_tokens, loop_break_count recorded.</check>
      <check>Multi-agent only: each agent has exactly one responsibility and a non-overlapping tool surface.</check>
      <check>System prompt contains explicit "do not search the same query twice" rule when web_search is exposed.</check>
    </checklist>
    <section name="Prompt Patterns for Agent Pattern Selection">
      <prompt purpose="pattern-selection"><![CDATA[<agent_pattern_selection>
  <task>{{describe the user goal in one sentence}}</task>
  <constraints>
    <tools_available>{{comma-separated tool names}}</tools_available>
    <max_steps>15</max_steps>
    <latency_budget_seconds>{{int}}</latency_budget_seconds>
  </constraints>
  <candidate_patterns>CoT, ReAct, Plan-and-Execute</candidate_patterns>
  <decision_rules>
    <rule>If task is pure reasoning over the prompt -> CoT.</rule>
    <rule>If task needs tools and has <= 5 sequential steps -> ReAct.</rule>
    <rule>If task has > 5 steps or branching dependencies -> Plan-and-Execute.</rule>
  </decision_rules>
  <output_format>JSON with keys: chosen_pattern, rationale, initial_plan (only if Plan-and-Execute, list of {id, action, depends_on}).</output_format>
</agent_pattern_selection>]]></prompt>
      <prompt purpose="react-system-prompt"><![CDATA[<react_loop>
  <system>You are a research agent. For each iteration, output exactly:
Thought: <one sentence reasoning>
Action: <tool_name>(<json_args>)
Then STOP and wait for an Observation message before continuing.
Output Final Answer: <answer> only when the task is fully complete.

Rules:
- Never call the same tool with the same args twice.
- Never invent Observation values; wait for the runtime to inject them.
- If after 3 attempts you cannot make progress, output: Final Answer: BLOCKED <reason>.</system>
  <task>{{research_task}}</task>
</react_loop>]]></prompt>
      <prompt purpose="plan-and-execute"><![CDATA[<plan_and_execute>
  <system>You are a planning agent. Output a JSON plan first, then execute each step.

Plan schema:
{
  "goal": string,
  "steps": [
    {"id": int, "action": string, "tool": string, "args": object, "depends_on": [int]}
  ]
}

After each step, output:
{"step_id": int, "status": "completed"|"failed", "result": any, "error": string|null}

If any step fails, emit a "replan" event with the revised plan before continuing.</system>
  <goal>{{goal}}</goal>
</plan_and_execute>]]></prompt>
    </section>
    <section name="CLI Tools and Frameworks">
      <p>anthropic SDK provides core LLM calls for all patterns. langgraph is the state machine for Plan-and-Execute and complex ReAct with built-in persistence and graph visualization. autogen handles multi-agent conversation patterns where agents negotiate and debate. crewai provides role-based agent teams with built-in task prioritization. openai SDK is the OpenAI Agents SDK reference implementation. LangSmith is essential for pattern execution tracing and debugging. Modal provides sandboxed tool execution to prevent host contamination.</p>
      <list>
        <item>anthropic SDK — Core LLM calls for all patterns with native tool_use support. pip install anthropic</item>
        <item>langgraph — State machine for Plan-and-Execute and complex ReAct. Built-in graph visualization. pip install langgraph</item>
        <item>autogen — Multi-agent conversation pattern where agents negotiate. pip install pyautogen</item>
        <item>crewai — Role-based agent teams with task prioritization and backstory. pip install crewai</item>
        <item>openai SDK — OpenAI Agents SDK (tool use pattern reference and official OpenAI implementation). pip install openai</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <commands>
      <command name="install-anthropic">pip install --upgrade anthropic</command>
      <command name="install-langgraph">pip install --upgrade "langgraph&gt;=0.2,&lt;0.3" langsmith</command>
      <command name="install-crewai">pip install --upgrade crewai crewai-tools</command>
      <command name="install-autogen">pip install --upgrade pyautogen</command>
      <command name="enable-langsmith">export LANGCHAIN_TRACING_V2=true LANGCHAIN_API_KEY=$LANGSMITH_KEY LANGCHAIN_PROJECT=agent-patterns</command>
      <command name="run-react-benchmark">python -m bench.run --pattern react --tasks bench/tasks.jsonl --max-steps 15 --out runs/react.jsonl</command>
      <command name="run-plan-execute-benchmark">python -m bench.run --pattern plan-execute --tasks bench/tasks.jsonl --max-steps 25 --out runs/plan.jsonl</command>
      <command name="grade-benchmark">python -m bench.grade runs/react.jsonl --gold bench/gold.jsonl --metrics success_rate,avg_steps,p95_tokens,loop_break_count</command>
      <command name="detect-loops">jq -s 'group_by(.run_id) | map({run: .[0].run_id, repeats: ([.[] | .action] | group_by(.) | map(length) | max)}) | map(select(.repeats &gt; 2))' runs/react.jsonl</command>
    </commands>
    <example type="good" title="ReAct loop with anthropic SDK and guards">
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[import hashlib, json, anthropic
client = anthropic.Anthropic()
TOOLS = [{"name": "web_search", "description": "Search the public web. Returns top 5 results as JSON.", "input_schema": {"type": "object", "properties": {"query": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["query"]}}]
SYSTEM = "You are a research agent. Never call the same tool with the same args twice. After 15 iterations, return Final Answer: BLOCKED."

def run(task: str, max_steps: int = 15):
    history, seen = [{"role": "user", "content": task}], []
    for step in range(max_steps):
        resp = client.messages.create(model="claude-opus-4-7", system=SYSTEM, tools=TOOLS, messages=history, max_tokens=1024)
        if resp.stop_reason == "end_turn":
            return resp.content[-1].text
        for block in resp.content:
            if block.type == "tool_use":
                key = hashlib.sha1(json.dumps([block.name, block.input], sort_keys=True).encode()).hexdigest()
                if seen[-3:].count(key) >= 1 and len(seen) >= 3 and seen[-3:] == [key, key, key]:
                    return "BLOCKED: loop detected"
                seen.append(key)
                obs = call_tool(block.name, block.input)
                history += [{"role": "assistant", "content": resp.content}, {"role": "user", "content": [{"type": "tool_result", "tool_use_id": block.id, "content": json.dumps(obs)}]}]
    return "BLOCKED: max_steps"]]></code>
      <note>Loop guard, max_steps cap, and deterministic JSON tool output are all visible in fewer than 25 lines. This is the minimal correct ReAct implementation.</note>
    </example>
    <example type="bad" title="ReAct without guards">
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[# DO NOT SHIP — no max_steps, no loop detection, free-text observations
while True:
    resp = client.messages.create(model="claude-opus-4-7", messages=history, tools=TOOLS)
    for block in resp.content:
        if block.type == "tool_use":
            history.append({"role": "user", "content": str(call_tool(block.name, block.input))})]]></code>
      <note>This loops forever on ambiguous tool output and burns the API budget within minutes.</note>
    </example>
    <verify>
      <step>1. Run the chosen pattern on the 10-20 task benchmark: <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[python -m bench.run --pattern <chosen> --tasks bench/tasks.jsonl --out runs/<chosen>.jsonl]]></code></step>
      <step>2. Grade results and assert thresholds: <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[python -m bench.grade runs/<chosen>.jsonl --gold bench/gold.jsonl --assert success_rate>=0.7 avg_steps<=10 p95_tokens<=20000 loop_break_count==0]]></code></step>
      <step>3. Inspect at least one trace end-to-end in LangSmith (or the JSONL log) and confirm: thoughts are non-repetitive, tool args are well-formed JSON, observations are deterministic.</step>
      <step>4. Run loop-detection over the run log and confirm zero (action, args) tuples repeat 3+ times: <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[jq -s 'group_by(.run_id) | map({run: .[0].run_id, repeats: ([.[] | .action] | group_by(.) | map(length) | max)}) | map(select(.repeats > 2))' runs/<chosen>.jsonl]]></code></step>
      <step>5. Plan-and-Execute only: confirm at least one replan event fired in test runs where a step was forced to fail. If replan never fires, the trigger is wired wrong.</step>
      <step>6. Token budget check: total tokens per task at p95 must be within the budget set in the task brief; if not, downgrade pattern or trim tools.</step>
    </verify>
    <section name="Services and Observability Tools">
      <p>LangGraph is OSS and best for stateful Plan-and-Execute but has a steep learning curve. AutoGen is OSS (Microsoft) for multi-agent conversation with role specialization. CrewAI is OSS with a simpler API than AutoGen. OpenAI Agents SDK is official OpenAI but tightly coupled to OpenAI models. LangSmith is SaaS for pattern execution tracing and is essential for ReAct debugging. Modal is SaaS for sandboxed tool execution.</p>
      <list>
        <item>LangGraph — OSS. Best for stateful Plan-and-Execute. Steep learning curve.</item>
        <item>AutoGen — OSS (Microsoft). Multi-agent conversation. Good for role specialization.</item>
        <item>CrewAI — OSS. Role-based teams. Simpler API than AutoGen.</item>
        <item>OpenAI Agents SDK — SaaS/OSS. Official OpenAI. Tightly coupled to OpenAI models.</item>
        <item>LangSmith — SaaS. Pattern execution tracing. Essential for ReAct debugging.</item>
        <item>Modal — SaaS. Sandboxed tool execution for Tool Use Pattern.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <p>Match pattern to task structure before selecting a framework: CoT for pure reasoning, ReAct for tool-dependent research, Plan-and-Execute for multi-step workflows with dependencies. This matching step is the single most important decision — the right pattern on a small model beats the wrong pattern on a large model.</p>
      <p>Implement explicit loop-detection: if the last 3 Thought to Action cycles are identical, break and return an error rather than continuing indefinitely. This prevents agents from wasting tokens on repetitive cycles.</p>
      <p>Use structured output (JSON schema) for Plan-and-Execute plan steps; free-text plans degrade execution reliability. The agent is more likely to follow a structured plan with explicit task IDs and dependencies than a narrative description.</p>
      <p>Test each pattern on a known-answer benchmark before production deployment; patterns that work on toy examples often fail on real tasks. Run each pattern on 10-20 representative tasks and measure success rate before shipping.</p>
      <p>For multi-agent patterns (AutoGen, CrewAI), assign exactly one responsibility per agent; agents with overlapping roles produce contradictory outputs. If Agent A can do both data gathering and analysis, and Agent B can do analysis, they will conflict on analysis tasks.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Common Gotchas">
      <p>ReAct agents with access to a general web-search tool will spend iterations searching for information they already have in context. They will search for "Python 3.11 release date" ten times if the context grows large enough that the agent forgets it saw that information already. Set a no_redundant_search rule in the system prompt: "Do not search for the same query twice. If you find the answer once, use it."</p>
      <p>Plan-and-Execute agents that don't replan after a failed step will complete all remaining steps against an invalid intermediate state. If step 3 fails because a data source is unavailable but steps 4-7 all depend on step 3's output, the agent will proceed to steps 4-7 with garbage input and produce worthless output. Implement a check after each step: if status != completed, replan or fail.</p>
      <p>CoT prompting ("Let's think step by step") works on Claude and GPT-4 but degrades on smaller models and on non-English languages; don't assume it transfers. Test CoT on your target model and language before production deployment.</p>
      <p>Framework abstractions (LangGraph, CrewAI) hide token costs; always instrument token usage per agent call, not per framework invocation. A LangGraph graph might invoke the model 5 times internally but the framework won't report token usage per call. Use LangSmith or manual logging to track costs.</p>
      <p>The Tool Use Pattern requires tools to return deterministic, parseable output; tools that return HTML, markdown, or unstructured text cause the agent to hallucinate parsed results. If a web search tool returns raw HTML, the agent will extract the wrong information or make up facts about what it thinks the HTML contains. Preprocess tool outputs to extract structure before returning to the agent.</p>
    </section>
